<p>When I returned to work after I had my daughter, I decided toÂ work part-time. I was demoted. My responsibilities were slashed and a childless colleague with very littleÂ communications experience was given my job.</p>
<p>It was humiliating. I&#8217;d workedÂ full-time in mostly female dominated industries and believedÂ we lived in more enlightened times. I couldn&#8217;t have been more wrong.</p>
<p>As a mother I was no longer prime employee real estate. Welcome to the reality of inequality in the workplace.</p>
<p><strong>And I&#8217;m FAR from alone.</strong></p>
<p>Nearly EVERY mother I know has a similar tale to tell of either blatant discrimination or the dawning realisation that the career they once thrived in is incompatibleÂ with being a mum.</p>
<p><strong>Every year 54,000 women are forced out of their jobs by unsympathetic employers after maternity leave.</strong></p>
<h1>The reality of inequality in the workplace</h1>
<p>Itâ€™s not only that mothers donâ€™t wantÂ to commute for twoÂ hours and put in a 15 hour shift at the office. They canâ€™t.</p>
<p>The main responsibility for childcare &#8211; and most other forms of care for that matter &#8211; still lies with women. And the reason for this lies squarely with the outdated notion of working nine-to-five.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: bold;">The traditional workplace is a toxic environment for mothers.</span></p>
<hr />
<p>	<span class="label label-primary">Related:</span>
	Â <a href="https://emmalouisesmith.com/freedom-flexible-working/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Bye bye nine-to-five, hello freedom and flexible working</a></p>
<hr />
<p>This working world we&#8217;ve inherited became the norm when 99% of the workforce were men with wives at home taking care of the home and the children. Times have changed, but our working life hasn&#8217;t.</p>
<p>Despite the lip service paid to &#8216;flexible working&#8217; by many employers, workingÂ nine-to-fiveÂ still remains the norm. And while it doesÂ anyone who has the audacity to request more flexibility ends up being viewed as less committed. This couldnâ€™t be further from the truth.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: bold;">One in five new mums experience harassment or negative comments from their colleagues, employer or manager when pregnant or returning from maternity leave.</span></p>
<p>Just because you donâ€™t want to work 15 hour days Â and canâ€™t go for spontaneous after work drinks anymore doesnâ€™t mean you arenâ€™t a dedicated, loyal and high performing employee.</p>
<p>As a part-time working mother I was ten times more productive than I ever was when I worked full-time. With limited time to get everything done I powered through and ditched the time-wasting.</p>
<p>Yet, my absence from the office two days a week and theÂ fact I had to leaveÂ at 5pm on the dot left me withÂ the distinct impression that others feltÂ IÂ wasn&#8217;t pulling my weight.</p>
<h1>The stark choice mothers face</h1>
<p>Despite the circumstances I was lucky to have an employer who even considered allowingÂ me to work part-time. After having kids most women faceÂ two stark choices:</p>
<ol>
<li>Struggle on in a full-time role desperately trying to keep all the balls in the air â€“ OR</li>
<li>Give up work because the hours, commuting and childcare costs make it not worth yourÂ while.</li>
</ol>
<p>Iâ€™d like to think there was a third option but flexible, part-time roles that are both rewarding and well-paid are a bit of an urban myth.</p>
<p>Outside London the vast majority of part-time work is unskilled and poorly paid. If you donâ€™t believe me do a quick search on any local jobs site. There&#8217;s a dearthÂ ofÂ appealing options.</p>
<p><strong>A shocking 54% of women who workÂ part-time are doing jobs below their experience and qualifications.</strong></p>
<h1><span style="font-weight: bold;">Itâ€™s a shocking waste of talent</span></h1>
<p>As if that wasnâ€™t ridiculous enough, here&#8217;s what&#8217;sÂ REALLY absurd:</p>
<ul>
<li>This isnâ€™t a challenge facingÂ a tiny minority of our society. Itâ€™s an issue nearly EVERY woman in this country faces when she has children.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Forcing us allÂ toÂ pile onto the same trains, buses and roads every morning so we canÂ sit behind a desk in a soulless, natural light-starved office is COMPLETELY UNNECESSARY.</li>
</ul>
<p>Most of us have all the technology and equipment we need to work from wherever we darn well please in our back pockets â€“ or our handbags!</p>
<p>Armed with a smartphone, or perhapsÂ a laptop and a wifi connection, you can work from wherever you please, whenever you please.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: bold;">Weâ€™re not ploughing fields, or on the production line in factories anymore so why are we clinging on to working the same eight hours, Monday to Friday?</span></p>
<p>Itâ€™s not even productive. You lose the ability to concentrate effectively after staring at a computer screen for two hours. Regular breaks, as well as working at times that suit you &#8211; weâ€™re not all the same! &#8211; increase your productivity.</p>
<p>So does the feeling of having some control over your life.</p>
<p>Two thirds of MPs believe it would boost the economy if employees could work more flexibly.</p>
<h1><span style="font-weight: bold;">So why does the nine-to-five survive?</span></h1>
<p>Because most of us simply accept what we&#8217;reÂ used to. But the days of sheep like acceptance are coming to an end.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: bold;">Between 2008 and 2015 the number of mothers working as freelancers increased by a massive 70%.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: bold;">70%! Thatâ€™s HUGE!</span></p>
<hr />
<p>	<span class="label label-primary">Related:</span>
	Â <a href="https://emmalouisesmith.com/advantages-of-self-employment/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">18 advantages of self-employment for single mums</a></p>
<hr />
<p>Determined not to waste their talent, education and ambition professional mothers are voting with their feet, and seeking a better way. And I unashamedly encourage you to do the same.</p>
<h1><span style="font-weight: bold;">JUST SAY NO.</span></h1>
<ul>
<li>No to being a bum on a seat between nine and five, being judged by your visibility instead of your ability.</li>
<li>No to spending two hours of your day packed into public transport like a sardine in a can.</li>
<li>No to an outdated, unproductive model of working life that pilesÂ unnecessary amounts of stress and guiltÂ onto your shoulders.</li>
</ul>
<p>Until we start saying no, loudly and firmly, employers won&#8217;t listen. Until thenÂ they have carte blanche to carry on expecting usÂ to work in an outdated, unproductive way that is toxic to family life.</p>
<p><strong>The lip service they pay to flexible work as a &#8216;benefit&#8217; isn&#8217;t enough.</strong></p>
<p>It&#8217;s not a benefit. It&#8217;s how we should all live. A genuinely flexible approach to working hours would create a level playing field where both parents would be able to fit work around the school run and administer the Calpol in flu season. Not just mothers.</p>
<p>But until then it will always be predominantly mothers who choose to opt out. Because someone has to.</p>
<p>So I choose not to miss out onÂ my daughterâ€™s childhood or sacrifice my ambitions, because my employer refuses to allowÂ me someÂ control over my life.</p>
<p>I deserve more, my daughter certainly does â€“ and so do you.</p>
